## Problem
Mode A / hark need a **deterministic** way to pick argv for coding agents: prefer short aliases (`cc`, `cx`, `gk`, `cr`) when safe, else canonical CLI (`claude`, `codex`, `grok`, `cursor-agent`). Ad-hoc CLIs must work without a catalog entry. Naive PATH lookup is wrong on real hosts (`cc` → gcc; `cr` → CodeRabbit).

## Scope (I005 / B055)
Resolver only — no herdr spawn yet.

## Design
- Module e.g. `hark.agents.resolve` (or `hark.cli_resolve`).
- Built-in catalog for: claude (`cc`), codex (`cx`), grok (`gk`), cursor-agent (`cr`); also known peers (opencode, pi, agy) without requiring short aliases.
- For each agent: try preferred aliases then canonical name; accept first `shutil.which` hit that passes **reject** checks.
- Reject: basename `cc` that is gcc/cc→gcc; basename `cr` that is coderabbit; other non-coding collisions as needed.
- **Ad-hoc**: free-form argv list / command string → normalized `list[str]` with no alias magic (optional shell-split rules: simple, no full shell).
- Config hooks later (B059); resolver should accept optional override map in API for tests.
- Public API sketch: `resolve_agent_argv(name_or_alias: str, *, extra_args=(), overrides=None) -> ResolvedCli` with fields `agent_key`, `argv`, `source` (`alias`|`canonical`|`override`|`adhoc`).

## Acceptance
- [ ] Unit tests: prefer alias when safe; fall back to canonical; reject gcc-as-cc and coderabbit-as-cr
- [ ] Ad-hoc argv path works without catalog entry
- [ ] Override map wins when provided
- [ ] No dependency on interactive fish/zsh functions
- [ ] Documented pitfalls in module docstring (link plan I005)